<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Wed Nov 27 21:27:33 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I visited The Wall for the first time in May, 1996, twenty six years after my return from the Vietnam War.<br><br>
It's effect on me was a profound and emotional experience, the words for which I wrote down. When I go back to the words, it is like returning to The Wall. My younger Daughter gave me a print of The Wall for Father's Day. It portrays a man with his head on the wall and the ghosts of his memories in the reflection. She said that I was that man. She knew and she could in some way feel my pain. I cried for hours afterward. I have it hung in a place where I see it several times a day.<br><br>
My experience at The Wall pushed me onward on a journey to find the parts of me that were buried by my experiences during the war and after my return. To me the wall is as much as part of life as it is death. <br><br>
  
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


